\begin_layout Plain Layout
This diagram shows the space of all functions.
 The hypothesis space 
\begin_inset Formula $\cf$
\end_inset

 carves out a subset of that space.
 The Bayes prediction function 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 will not typically be contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\cf$
\end_inset

.
 The best we can possibly do in terms of risk (i.e.
 the expected loss on a new randomly chosen data point), which is our ultimate
 performance measure, is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\cf}$
\end_inset

.
 How much worse does 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\cf}$
\end_inset

 perform than 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

? That's our potential penalty for restricting to a hypothesis space 
\begin_inset Formula $\cf$
\end_inset

.
 We hope it will be more than compensated by reduction in overfitting.
 We can write down that performance gap explicitly, and it's called approximatio
n error.
 (Parenthetically, Approximation theory is a field of mathematics that studies
 how well one can approximate a function by simpler functions – e.g.
 using polynomials, or sins and cosines or wavelets to approximate a given
 function.
 And studying how well these approximations work.) Approximaiton error of
 a hypothesis space 
\begin_inset Formula $\cf$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\risk(f_{\cf})-\risk(f^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 
